		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    A rich man's guide to becoming rich - volume 1</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:">Fael</a> | 
		            5/2/2001 4:40:27 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">Hello. I play 4 main characters on the Prexus server, which are a level 17 druid, a level 12 monk, a level 14 shadowknight and a level 10 druid. I had an 8k account until my SK&#8217;s corpse rotted, which then turned to 5k but is now 6k. I have looked over every money making guide on this web page and every one either looks underdeveloped, greedy and spiteful, or just plain stupid. That is why I am writing this. <BR>
<BR>
DEVELOPING WEALTH VOLUME 1<BR>
<BR>
The trick to becoming rich is definitely the buy/sell technique. A fair amount of killing things and looting is also great for becoming rich, but I will cover that in volume 2. From what I have seen, all other buy/sell guides say one thing, screw people over then screw other people over and make ALOT of money. This is not right; you can become rich without screwing people over, very rich in fact. Look at me, my highest char is level 17 and I have a 6k account. Anyway, the trick to buying/selling is quantity, not quality. Instead of selling your langseax to a newbie for 100pp... sell it in the upper scale of normal price. If an item runs from 20-30 PP, charge 28. Always make a profit, but it does NOT have to be large. You will sell things MUCH faster if you have reasonable prices and then you can buy cheap things faster. The idea here is to make a TON of transactions to make your money. Not only this, but often if you are nice and charge a fair amount, people will help you out later if your in need. I'd like to see what would happen if you ran into the war who bought a langseax (retailing 20pp) from you for 100pp. I don't think he would help you... Reputation is what matters, not the quick buck. Everquest has a real economy and, like in real life, if you toy with the economy it will eventually catch up with you. Keeping a good reputation will keep good customers and high frequency. Charge less if someone is buying in bulk, this way he will be more inclined to buy from you instead of the other guy. Always keep a good attitude and THANK people for their business. Always zone hop. Selling an item where it is looted will get you a significantly lower profit then selling it where it is rare. Supply and demand. Basically it is Capitalism 101. Please see volume 2 discussing loot and how to find the items you want to sell.<BR>

			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
			</td>
				<td>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td></tr>
